'''Wayne Lawrence Brown''' (born 20 August 1977 in [[Barking]], England) is an English [[association football|footballer]], who plays for [[Bury Town FC]]

==Career==
===Ipswich===
Brown started his career as an apprentice at [[Ipswich Town]], making 40 league appearances for the club and scoring once against [[FC Avenir Beggen|Avenir Beggen]] in the [[UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news 
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/uefa_cup/2221664.stm
|title=Ipswich thrash Beggen
|publisher=BBC 
|date=29 August 2002 |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>

===Watford===
He had loan spells at Colchester, [[QPR]] and [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] (where he scored once against [[Crewe Alexandra]])<ref>{{cite news 
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/1545764.stm
|title=Crewe 0<U+2013>4 Wimbledon
|publisher=BBC 
|date=18 September 2001 |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> before leaving the club in December 2002, signing for [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] after a loan spell. Whilst at Watford he had a loan spell at Gillingham, playing four games and scoring once against Walsall,<ref>{{cite news 
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/3125056.stm
|title=Walsall 2<U+2013>1 Gillingham
|publisher=BBC 
|date=29 September 2003 |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> before moving to [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] after a successful [[loan (football)|loan]] period.

===Colchester United===
He spent three seasons at [[Layer Road]] making 159 appearances and was the only outfield player to play every minute of every game in the [[Football League Championship]] in the [[2006<U+2013>07 in English football|2006<U+2013>07]] season. He was voted Colchester United's Player of the Season for [[2005<U+2013>06 in English football|2005<U+2013>06]]. He has yet to return the supporters player-of-the-season trophy to Colchester United despite numerous requests and the club have considered taking legal action.

===Hull City===
Brown signed a three-year contract with [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] on 14 July 2007 after Colchester agreed to sell him for <U+00A3>450,000.<ref name="Tigers wrap up transfer of Brown">{{cite news| title = Tigers wrap up transfer of Brown| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hull_city/6293212.stm|publisher=BBC Sport| date = 14 July 2007| accessdate =15 July 2007}}</ref> In his first season with Hull, he helped them win promotion to the [[Premier League]],<ref name="Bristol City 0-1 Hull">{{cite news|title = Bristol City 0<U+2013>1 Hull|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_1/7416502.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date = 24 May 2008|accessdate =14 February 2010|first=Phil|last=McNulty}}</ref> with Brown scoring once in the process against former club Ipswich.<ref>{{cite news 
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/7008065.stm
|title=Hull 3<U+2013>1 Ipswich 
|publisher=BBC 
|work=BBC Sport
|date=29 September 2007 |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> On 27 October 2008, Brown joined [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on loan for a month, having been found surplus to requirements at his parent club.<ref name="Preston sign Hull defender Brown">{{cite news| title = Preston sign Hull defender Brown| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/preston/7693939.stm|publisher=BBC Sport| date = 27 October 2008| accessdate =27 October 2008}}</ref>
[[File:Hobbs & Brown.png|thumb|left|[[Jack Hobbs (footballer)|Jack Hobbs]] and Wayne Brown playing for [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].]]
On 30 August 2008, Brown made his Premier League debut for Hull City in a 5<U+2013>0 loss against Wigan. During the game, Brown made a mistake when he allowed [[Amr Zaki|Zaki]] to score the third goal in the match.<ref name="Hull 0-5 Wigan">{{Cite news
 | title =  Hull 0<U+2013>5 Wigan
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7578446.stm
 |publisher=BBC
 |work=BBC Sport
 | date = 30 August 2008
 | accessdate =5 September 2011
 | first=Russell
 | last=Barder}}</ref>

===Leicester City===
On 30 January 2009, Brown joined [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on loan for the rest of the 2008<U+2013>09 season with a view to a permanent transfer in the summer.<ref name="Brown Turns Blue">{{cite news| title=Brown Turns Blue| url=http://www.lcfc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~1538409,00.html| publisher=LCFC.co.uk| date=3 January 2009| accessdate=30 January 2009}}</ref> He helped the club regain promotion to the Championship as [[Football League One|League One]] champions by beating [[Southend United]] 2<U+2013>0 on 18 April 2009.<ref name="Southend 0-2 Leicester">{{cite news|title = Southend 0<U+2013>2 Leicester|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_2/7990038.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date = 18 April 2009|accessdate =14 February 2010}}</ref> On 28 April 2009, Brown signed a two-year deal with the club for an undisclosed fee.<ref name="Brown seals permanent Foxes deal">{{cite news| title=Brown seals permanent Foxes deal| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/8022294.stm|work=BBC Sport| publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation| date=28 April 2009| accessdate=28 April 2009}}</ref> He went on to make 39 appearances in the 2009<U+2013>10 season, helping Leicester concede just 45 goals and finish in the Championship playoff places.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/table/default.stm |work=BBC News | title=The Npower Football League Championship: Table | date=17 December 2009}}</ref> On 15 May 2010, it was revealed that Brown was under investigation by the club following an alleged training ground bust-up over comments he made regarding over the outcome of the UK General Election.<ref>http://www.thebluearmy.co.uk/news/brown-face-bust-inquiry/article-2159509-detail/article.html</ref> Brown voted for the far-right [[British National Party]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1278734/Revealed-What-BNP-supporter-Wayne-Brown-said-enrage-Leicester-team-mates.html |location=London |work=Daily Mail  | title=Revealed: What BNP supporter Wayne Brown said to enrage his Leicester team-mates | first=Derek | last=Hunter | date=16 May 2010}}</ref>  On 5 July 2010 Brown had a medical at Preston North End. The next day it was revealed that Brown had left Leicester City by mutual consent.

===Preston North End===
It was announced on the [[Preston North End FC|Preston North End]] official website that Brown had become a Preston player following his release by mutual consent from [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]<ref>http://www.pnefc.net/page/NewsDetail/0,,10362~2085370,00.html</ref>

===Bury Town===

Brown joined Bury Town in the 2011<U+2013>12 season after been told that he wouldn't be picked by Preston boss Phil Brown.

